    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1039113203" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1039113203" />
    <a title="Robert Blumenthal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10110896-robert-blumenthal"><img alt="Robert Blumenthal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1339293952p2/10110896.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1039113203?book_show_action=true">Aug 28, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Blumenthal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Blumenthal" href="/user/show/10110896-robert-blumenthal">Robert Blumenthal</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1039113203" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13032217664456230616">This is a book that the author wrote about 7 years ago, given to me by a friend. I have become enamored with Alice Hoffman after neglecting her books for years (I think her last two books were both exceptional). This one is essentially a modern day fairy tale, and it teeters on the fantastical throughout though deals with the very heart of human emotions. At times I had decided I would give this book only 4 stars, but Ms. Hoffman wraps it up so superbly that I decided on adding that ultimate sta</span>
  <span id="freeText13032217664456230616" style="display:none">This is a book that the author wrote about 7 years ago, given to me by a friend. I have become enamored with Alice Hoffman after neglecting her books for years (I think her last two books were both exceptional). This one is essentially a modern day fairy tale, and it teeters on the fantastical throughout though deals with the very heart of human emotions. At times I had decided I would give this book only 4 stars, but Ms. Hoffman wraps it up so superbly that I decided on adding that ultimate star. The narrator, when she is eight-years old, wishes her mother to be dead on an impulse as she is driving away on a winter evening. Subsequently, the mother dies in a car accident, and the daughter takes the blame for it. She is deeply repressed for her adult life until she is struck by lightening, which alters her life in various ways. She becomes involved with other people who have been struck by lightening and also maintains a troubled relationship with her only brother, who is 4 years older than her. I sped through this book and became quite involved in it. As I stated previously, the ending is very rich and extremely satisfying. I was profoundly moved my it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13032217664456230616" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


